We=E2=80=99re not hearing of many departures from contemporary art, for exa=
mple. And the way the auction business works, Sotheby=E2=80=99s thinning th=
e ranks of specialists doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily put it in a less competi=
tive position. Even after the growth of Phillips and the brightening prospe=
cts of Bonhams, the auction world remains a duopoly. On any big estate or c=
onsignment of property, sellers will always want to get a competitive bid f=
rom the other side.

As we saw with the Sydell Miller estate, the power of Sotheby=E2=80=99s pla=
tform can be activated by a small, well-organized team working for the cons=
ignor. This has been done before. In 2010, Phillips partnered with Philippe=
 S=C3=A9galot to mount the $117 million Carte Blanche sale. S=C3=A9galot, a=
 former Christie=E2=80=99s head of contemporary art, did most of the work=
=E2=80=94assembling the property,
cultivating the bidders, and even manning the phones at the sale. For one n=
ight, he was a one-man contemporary art department=E2=80=A6 and the sale wa=
s a rousing success. With the army of former auction house specialists now =
freelancing as art advisors and Sotheby=E2=80=99s sterling name, the compan=
y could easily run these sorts of asset-light auctions in its new sale room=
s at the Breuer on Madison Avenue.

A year ago, Stewart attended Gagosian gallery=E2=80=99s show ( https://gago=
sian.com/exhibitions/2023/a-foreigner-called-picasso-curated-by-annie-cohen=
-solal-and-verane-tasseau/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F=
10%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F10%2F24%29&utm_me=
dium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a =
) of Picasso works, curated by writer Annie Cohen-Solal, and came away deep=
ly impressed and excited by the prospect of mounting his
own museum-quality shows. He wondered aloud to several of his staff what it=
 would take, not seeming to understand that all his team lacked were the fu=
nds=E2=80=94and time=E2=80=94to mount such a show, let alone several of the=
m a year. A person familiar with the planning of the Gagosian show told me =
that the insurance fees on the eight-figure paintings on loan were not for =
the weak of heart.

But with a showcase like the Breuer building, where many decades of museum =
shows generated lines around the block, Sotheby=E2=80=99s ought to have a m=
ajor draw for its stable of corporate sponsors to offset the expense. In ot=
her words, there=E2=80=99s no obvious reason why Sotheby=E2=80=99s cannot t=
hrive with a reduced focus on fine art.

At this moment, the auction houses have never had such different business s=
trategies. The restructuring at Sotheby=E2=80=99s this month recognizes the=
ir diverging paths. That said, Sotheby=E2=80=99s new strategy will require =
the kind of flawless execution that proved elusive
in today=E2=80=99s layoffs.

