          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">We=E2=80=99re not h=
earing of many departures from contemporary art, for example. And the way t=
he auction business works, Sotheby=E2=80=99s thinning the ranks of speciali=
sts doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily put it in a less competitive position. Even=
 after the growth of Phillips and the brightening prospects of Bonhams, the=
 auction world remains a duopoly. On any big estate or consignment of prope=
rty, sellers will always want to get a competitive bid from the other side.=
<br/><br/>As we saw with the <b>Sydell Miller </b>estate, the power of Soth=
eby=E2=80=99s platform can be activated by a small, well-organized team wor=
king for the consignor. This has been done before. In 2010, Phillips partne=
red with <b>Philippe S=C3=A9galot</b> to mount the $117 million Carte Blanc=
he sale. S=C3=A9galot, a former Christie=E2=80=99s head of contemporary art=
, did most of the work=E2=80=94assembling the property,
cultivating the bidders, and even manning the phones at the sale. For one n=
ight, he was a one-man contemporary art department=E2=80=A6 and the sale wa=
s a rousing success. With the army of former auction house specialists now =
freelancing as art advisors and Sotheby=E2=80=99s sterling name, the compan=
y could easily run these sorts of asset-light auctions in its new sale room=
s at the Breuer on Madison Avenue. <br/><br/>A year ago, Stewart attended <=
u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uk=
txclJLZ0dUc3dRQ0dsMFFiLTZmTm9TTG1NRT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9nYWdvc2lhbi5jb=
20vZXhoaWJpdGlvbnMvMjAyMy9hLWZvcmVpZ25lci1jYWxsZWQtcGljYXNzby1jdXJhdGVkLWJ5=
LWFubmllLWNvaGVuLXNvbGFsLWFuZC12ZXJhbmUtdGFzc2VhdS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPVdhbGw=
rUG93ZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxMiUyRjEwJTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD=
1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTIlMkYxMCUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZ=
Gl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rl=
cm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJ=
saW5rX2lkIjoyMDE0MTg4fQ/413138662f272ce43c6aca536d5114e220b6a2e502bc64f38f7=
1bfabae7806ae" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold=
" class=3D"sdf">Gagosian gallery=E2=80=99s show</a></u> of <b>Picasso </b>w=
orks, curated by writer <b>Annie Cohen-Solal</b>, and came away deeply impr=
essed and excited by the prospect of mounting his
own museum-quality shows. He wondered aloud to several of his staff what it=
 would take, not seeming to understand that all his team lacked were the fu=
nds=E2=80=94and time=E2=80=94to mount such a show, let alone several of the=
m a year. A person familiar with the planning of the Gagosian show told me =
that the insurance fees on the eight-figure paintings on loan were not for =
the weak of heart.<br/><br/>But with a showcase like the Breuer building, w=
here many decades of museum shows generated lines around the block, Sotheby=
=E2=80=99s ought to have a major draw for its stable of corporate sponsors =
to offset the expense. In other words, there=E2=80=99s no obvious reason wh=
y Sotheby=E2=80=99s cannot thrive with a reduced focus on fine art.  <br/><=
br/>At this moment, the auction houses have never had such different busine=
ss strategies. The restructuring at Sotheby=E2=80=99s this month recognizes=
 their diverging paths. That said, Sotheby=E2=80=99s new strategy will requ=
ire the kind of flawless execution that proved elusive
in today=E2=80=99s layoffs. <br/></td>
